2022-07-01

The Experiment

RNA-seq of induced pluripotent stem cells from monozygotic twins discordant for trisomy 21

Link Here

The Experiment

Down syndrome (trisomy 21) is the most common viable chromosomal disorder with intellectual impairment and several other developmental abnormalities. The experiment report the generation and characterization of induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) derived from monozygotic twins discordant for trisomy 21 in order to eliminate the effects of the variability of genomic background.

The Experiment

The Experiment

The alterations observed by genetic analysis at the iPSC level and at first approximation in early development illustrate the developmental disease transcriptional signature of Down syndrome. Moreover, we observed an abnormal neural differentiation of Down syndrome iPSCs in vivo when formed teratoma in NOD-SCID mice, and in vitro when differentiated into neuroprogenitors and neurons. These defects were associated with changes in the architecture and density of neurons, astroglial and oligodendroglial cells together with misexpression of genes involved in neurogenesis, lineage specification and differentiation.

mRNAseq Analysis

sampledata <- read.delim(file = 'E-GEOD-52249-experiment-design.tsv',
                         header = TRUE,
                         row.names = 1,
                         stringsAsFactors = TRUE)

Than I sorted the sampledata rows by rownames and counts coloumn by names. I did so because I was obtaining an error while trying to use the DESeqDataSetFromMatrix() function

sampledata <-sampledata[order(row.names(sampledata)), ] # sorting them by gene ids
counts <- counts[ , order(names(counts))]

mRNAseq Analysis

Ready to run the DESeqDataSetFromMatrix()

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(DESeq2))
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = counts,
                              colData = sampledata,  
                              design = as.formula("~ Factor.Value.disease."))

mRNAseq Analysis

After that I proceeded with the pipeline, DESeq() normalizes the counts and do estimation of dispersion values

dds <- DESeq(dds)

Than I create a PCA plot. In order to do that I used vst() function to normalize, it is more sensitive to library size than 'rlog().

vsd <- varianceStabilizingTransformation(dds)

mRNAseq Analysis

plotPCA(vsd, intgroup = 'Factor.Value.disease.') + 
  theme_bw()

From the PCA plots seems that all samples are correctly classified. Low variance between same group samples and high between different ones

mRNAseq Analysis

Darker is the color, more similar are the samples; trees represent the gerarchy of cluster. The heatmap suggest that all samples are correctly classified, DS samples are similar each other and same for Normal ones, as the PCA did.

# creating the Heat map
pheatmap(sampleDistMatrix,
         clustering_distance_rows = sampleDists,
         clustering_distance_cols = sampleDists,
         col = colors)

Gene Ontology (GO) Enrichment Analysis

Before the enrichment I added back the gene names to the results, to be able to perform the gene onthology analysis

library("AnnotationDbi")
library("org.Hs.eg.db")

DE$symbol <- mapIds(org.Hs.eg.db, # becous the sample are form Humans
                    keys=rownames(DE),
                    column="SYMBOL",
                    keytype="ENSEMBL",
                    multiVals="first")

Gene Ontology (GO) Enrichment Analysis

Analysis and plots

library(clusterProfiler)
GO_BP <- enrichGO(DE$symbol, OrgDb = "org.Hs.eg.db", 
                  keyType = "SYMBOL", ont = "BP")
GO_MF <- enrichGO(DE$symbol, OrgDb = "org.Hs.eg.db", 
                  keyType = "SYMBOL", ont = "MF")
GO_CC <- enrichGO(DE$symbol, OrgDb = "org.Hs.eg.db", 
                  keyType = "SYMBOL", ont = "CC")

More Plots

Volcano plot with EnhancedVolcano. On the plot there is the log2 fold change on the x axis while the pvalue on the y one. Pvalue cut off = 0.005 and Fold Change cut off = 2

EnhancedVolcano(DEresults,
                lab = DEresults$symbol,
                x = 'log2FoldChange',
                y = 'pvalue',
                title = 'Down syndrome versus Normal',
                pCutoff = 0.05,
                FCcutoff = 2,
                pointSize = 3.0,
                cutoffLineType = 'twodash',
                col = c('medium blue', 'steel blue', 'dodger blue', 'sky blue'),
                legendPosition = 'bottom',
                drawConnectors = TRUE,
                widthConnectors = 0.756,
                labSize = 5.0) + coord_flip()
